    • Class ca.gc.ic.broadcast.entity.Antenna extends java.lang.Object implements Serializable

      serialVersionUID:
      1L

      • Serialized Fields

        • pattKey

          java.lang.Integer pattKey
          The Antenna Radiation Pattern Key. This is used to attach RadiationPattern records to this Antenna.

        • polarization

          java.lang.String polarization
          Orientation. "H" for horizontal and "V" for vertical.

        • pattNumb

          java.lang.Double pattNumb
          Deprecated. Future use.

        • pattType

          java.lang.String pattType
          Type of pattern: 'PRECISE', 'BRIEF', 'THEORETICAL'.

          As part of the analysis of broadcast undertakings, antenna pattern data is lifted from tables in the brief or digitized from diagrams of the horizontal and vertical pattern.

          When no vertical antenna pattern data appears in the brief, a theoretical pattern for an antenna with the same number of bays is selected. In this case PATT_TYPE is set to "THEORETICAL".

          Omnidirectional Patterns: In the case of an Omnidirectional antenna, the Effective Radiated Power value from the main database is assumed to be the same for all azimuths. For this reason, no Horizontal pattern data is stored for Omnidirectional stations.

          Vertical Patterns: As described in the record layouts, the HOR_VER field is used to indicate a (H)orizontal or (V)ertical pattern. It is possible that a station with an Omnidirectional antenna may still have a Vertical antenna pattern, and this is supported.

          "THEORETICAL" Patterns: Very often measured patterns are not available at the time of the brief's analysis. In such cases, the department uses theoretical vertical patterns based on the Cosine Law. They have names from BAY-2 to BAY-12, corresponding to the theoretical vertical patterns of a two bay antenna, up to that of a twelve bay antenna.

          "BRIEF"/"PRECISE" Patterns: When pattern values area taken from a table in a technical brief, PATT_TYPE is set to "BRIEF". If the values are digitized from antenna diagrams, PATT_TYPE is set to "PRECISE".

        • punits

          java.lang.Double punits
          Deprecated. Future use.

        • numpoints

          java.lang.Double numpoints
          Number of points in the pattern.

        • pattDate

          java.lang.String pattDate
          Date pattern added to system.

        • canadaStationList

          java.util.List<E> canadaStationList
          Reverse pointer to one or more CanadaStations using this Antenna.

        • radiationPatternList

          java.util.List<E> radiationPatternList
          A list of 'gains' versus 'angle' data points defining the antenna pattern.

      • Serialized Fields

        • banner

          ECanadaBanner banner
          The Industry Canada station banner code.

          The Banner's transmitting field can be interrogated to determine whether the station is on or off air. TRUE means the station is transmitting and should be protected.

          Depending upon the type of service the following Banner codes are transmitting: [AP, AU, O, OP, TO].

          The station call sign. All Canadian station call signs begin with the letter 'C'.

          Beam Tilt Angle in Degrees; -10.0 to 10.0

          Closed Captioning; Y or N

          java.lang.Double haat
          Effective Height of Antenna Above Terrain

          -1,200.0 to 2,000.0 meters

        • erpaav

          java.lang.Double erpaav
          ERP Aural Average in Watts

          0 to 1,000,000

        • erpapk

          java.lang.Double erpapk
          ERP Aural Peak Power in Watts

          0 to 1,000,000

        • erpata

          java.lang.Integer erpata
          The Documentation claims this is the ERP Average Power at Tilt Angle in watts [0 to 5,000,000]. However, FCC guidance and the data indicate that this field is used to positively differentiate Analog or Digital operation as follows:

          The modulation field specifies the type of operation (analog or digital). TV modulation information is contained in the table column ERPATA and coded as 0=Analog; 1=Digital and 2=Post-transition.

          Developer note: 07/10/13: The canada 'tvstatio' database table contains the following values for this field [0, 1, 2], with active records showing the following values [0, 1].

        • erpvpk

          java.lang.Double erpvpk
          ERP Visual Peak Power in Watts.

          This value is used by default. If not set then the ERP Visual Average CanadaStationTv.erpvav is used.

          Documentation allows range of 0 to over 5,000,000. Database range is 0 to 846,000.

        • erpvav

          java.lang.Double erpvav
          ERP Visual Average in Watts

          Database range is 0 to 609,000.

        • erpvta

          java.lang.Double erpvta
          ERP Peak Visual Power at Tilt Angle in Watts

          Documentation allows range of 0 to over 5,000,000. This field is not set in the database (always zero).

        • towerElevation

          java.lang.Double towerElevation
          Ground Level at Tower Base above Sea Level in Meters. (AMSL)

          Documentation allows range of 0.0 to 9,999.9. Database range is 0 to 2955.

        • limitCode

          java.lang.String limitCode
          Deprecated. Not used in logical data model.
          Limitation Identification code "LAAAA".

        • offSetPrecision

          java.lang.Character offSetPrecision
          Refers to Off-set Precision. Valid Y, Space.

        • offSetCode

          java.lang.Character offSetCode
          Refers to TV Off-set Code. Space, +, -, Z.

        • overallHag

          java.lang.Double overallHag
          Overall Height Above ground in Meters

          Documentation allows range of 0.0 to 999.9. Database range is 0 to 797.

        • radCenter

          java.lang.Double radCenter
          Radiating Center Above Mean Sea Level in meters. (AMSL)

          Developer note: The BDBS documentation appears to be in error and cites this values as "Radiating Center Above Ground Level 0.0 to 5,000.0 metres". However the earlier document entry for FM stations identifies this field as "Above Mean Sea Level 0.0 to 5000.0 metres"

          Documentation allows range of 0.0 to 5,000.0 meters. Database range is 0 to 2790.
